@{fg shine}@{bg fill}NetPar Printer Spool Message #4@{bg back}

                Fatal Network Error

                Unable to find usergroup.library

                Please consult documentation

                NetParSpool will restart connection

                or be forced to abort@{fg text}

                This library is part of AmiTCP and
                Miami installations. It is used to lookup
                the user name of the user logged into
                the network.


@{fg shine}@{bg fill}NetPar Printer Spool Message #5@{fg text}@{bg back}

                @{fg shine}Fatal Network Printer Error

                Line Printer Daemon returned an

                Acknowledgment error. Transfer is

                Aborted and Spooler is terminated.@{fg text}


                The server failed to send a required
                acknowledgement or send an incorrect
                signal. The problem is probably with
                the server.


@{fg shine}@{bg fill}NetPar Printer Spool Message #6@{fg text}@{bg back}

                @{fg shine}Fatal Network Error

                Spooler was unable to find your

                Computer's Hostname (localhost)

                Please consult your TCP/IP stack

                documentation on how to add your

                host machine name to the network

                Spooler will be aborted@{fg text}

                A GetHostName() function has failed.
                In Miami, you can add the hostname in
                the Database/Hosts area and in the
                TCP/IP Host Name area.
                In AmiTCP, you can add your hostname
                to the AmiTCP:db/hosts area.


@{fg shine}@{bg fill}NetPar Printer Spool Message #7@{fg text}@{bg back}

               @{fg shine} Fatal Network Error

                Spooler was unable to find your

                user login id. Please consult your

                TCP/IP stack documentation on how to

                add a default user login id to the

                network. Spooler will be aborted@{fg text}

                In Miami, you need to add the user
                login in the Database/Users area AND
                in the TCP/IP - Real User name area.

                In AmiTCP, add your login to the
                AmiTCP:db/passwd file and also to
                the startnet script.


@{fg shine}@{bg fill}NetPar Printer Spool Message #8@{fg text}@{bg back}

                @{fg shine}Fatal Printer Spool Error

                Unable to lock or examine your spool

                directory.

                (NetPar/SpoolDir = @{fg text}"SpoolDir"@{fg shine} )

                The most probable cause is from a

                non-existant directory or a lingering

                dos lock. Spooler will be aborted@{fg text}


                This error is pretty much, self explanatory.
                The only option may be to reboot your computer
                in order to clear out the lingering dos lock.


@{fg shine}@{bg fill}NetPar Printer Spool Message #9@{fg text}@{bg back}

                @{fg shine}Fatal Network Printer Error

                Authentication or Printer error.

                User login, or Host machine not allowed

                to print. Or selected Printer name does

                not exist. Spooler will be aborted@{fg text}


                The printer you selected does not exists on the
                server, or else your machine does not have
                permission to use the server resources. Verify
                your settings and network permissions and try
                again. You may want to clear out the spool
                directory if you find the error is on your
                settings.


@{fg shine}@{bg fill}NetPar Printer Spool Message #10@{fg text}@{bg back}

                @{fg shine}Spooler was able to connect to

                printer server. Previous error

                condition has been corrected.

                Spooling will now continue@{fg text}


                NetPar will attempt to connect to the
                server twice before it exits with an
                error. This message is telling you that
                the previous error has been cleared
                up and NetPar will proceed as normal.
                You will also get this message if you
                tell NetPar to Wait on the network (See
                @{" Message #1 " link "Troubleshooting" 24} for details.) and the network
                 then becomes available.


@{fg shine}@{bg fill}NetPar Printer Spool Message #11@{fg text}@{bg back}

                @{fg shine}Spooler has been unable to connect

                to the printer server. The

                connection has failed twice. Spooler

                will now be aborted.@{fg text}

                Two attempt to connect to the server have
                failed. You should have gotton two error
                messages telling you what the problem is.
                Use those messages to troubleshoot your
                system.


@{fg shine}@{bg fill}NetPar Printer Spool Message #12@{fg text}@{bg back}

                @{fg shine}Spooler has been unable to connect

                to the printer server. The Host's

                Network address is unknown.

                Printer Host = ->@{fg text}"PrinterHOST"@{fg shine}<-

                NetParSpooler will restart connection

                or be forced to abort.@{fg text}


                Your computer attempted to look up the
                IP address of the print server you want
                to print to, but was unable to find it.
                This points to some type of network
                problem. In Miami, you can normally
                fix this problem by adding your printer
                host to the Database/Hosts area. In
                AmiTCP, you can fix this by adding the
                printer host to the AmiTCP:db/hosts
                file.

                If your Printer Host is "UNKNOWN", then
                NetPar was unable to find the PrinterHOST
                variable on your selected unit. Check to
                see which port you were using and then
                use the install script to verify you
                have a printer host name set for
                that unit.

*
@endnode

