@node "Users" "Users Contributions"
 @{b}@{fg shine}Pagestream Contributions@{ub}@{fg text}



@{b} ============================================================
 /* SetNetparPrinter.rexx                                  */
 /*                                                        */
 /* Set Netpar to print to a specific unit # (default 0)   */
 /* by setting the ActiveUnit environment variable         */
 /*                                                        */
 parse arg Unit

 if Unit = '' then Unit = 0

 address command 'setenv NetPar/ActiveUnit 'Unit
 ============================================================@{ub}


       @{fg shine}@{bg fill} Setting up PageStream3 with Netpar for Multiple Printers @{fg text}@{bg back}

If you have several different printers set up to work with NetPar, then changing
printers with PageStream requires two things:

    @{fg fill}@{bg shine}- Set the proper printer driver,@{fg text}@{bg back}

    @{fg fill}@{bg shine}- Set the 'ActiveUnit' environment variable for Netpar.@{fg text}@{bg back}

This can be done automatically via PageStream ("PgS") scripts, plus a tiny Arexx
script (supplied).  I'll assume here that NetPar is already installed, and that you
have two printers, called "MyPrinter1" and  "MyPrinter2".

The steps are:

  @{fg fill}@{bg shine} 1)@{fg text}@{bg back} Copy the supplied Arexx script "SetNetparPrinter.rexx" into the directory
"PageStream3:Scripts".  If you prefer another location, just change Step 3
accordingly.  This script does nothing but issue a  setenv command to AmigaDos for the
ActiveUnit variable.

  @{fg fill}@{bg shine} 2)@{fg text}@{bg back} For each printer, set up a preferences file within PgS.  This is done from the
Print Setup menu - after defining your printer  preferences, click on "Save As", and
save to a file such as:

      @{b}Softlogik:Printers/Styles/MyPrinter1.printer@{ub}

Again, if you use a different directory and/or name, change Step 3 accordingly.

  @{fg fill}@{bg shine} 3)@{fg text}@{bg back} Create separate scripts for each printer, within PgS.  To do this, access the
"Windows" menu item "Show Scripts Palette" within PgS.   In the palette window that
opens, click on the black arrow on the right, and access the menu item "new".  A
window opens to define a new script. Give a title that makes sense to you, such as
"Use MyPrinter1".  Type  the following in the Script dialog box:

      @{b}loadprintprefs file 'Softlogik:Printers/Styles/MyPrinter1.printer'@{ub}
     @{b} rx 'PageStream3:Scripts/SetNetparPrinter.rexx #'@{ub}

where "#" must be replaced by the Netpar unit number you defined for that printer.  I
suggest you also click to toggle on the box "Display in Menu".  If you wish, set up a
keyboard shortcut via the "Shortcut" box.  Click on "OK". That script should now show
up in the Scripts Palette window.  To save, be sure to click on the Palette black
arrow again, accessing menu item "Save". Repeat step 3 for each other printer, just
giving the script a different name, and different Netpar unit number.

You are now ready.  To use this, just activate the appropriate PgS menu (through the
Scripts menu, the Scripts palette window, and/or a keyboard shortcut).  

Please note that this has been tested only by myself, on one machine,  using three
network-ready PostScript printers.  Kindly send suggestions and corrections to me at
:

        @{fg shine}@{bg fill}  jconant@aerodyne.com  @{fg text}@{bg back}
        @{fg shine}@{bg fill}  John Conant           @{fg text}@{bg back}



   @{b}@{fg shine}ImageFX Contributions@{ub}@{fg text}


  Only problem I've encountered was with ImageFX 2.6 and it's "SuperPrefs" printing
module.  I expect the problem is with the 42.43  version of printer prefs not
netpar.device. The SuperPrefs module  will let the user change preference for the
print job without having  to run the regular preference program. The original
installation  would tell ImageFX what printer was set in preferences.  With  prt42_50
ImageFX hangs with the printer field blank.  The PrintMgr  program shows ImageFX job
"waiting". Only way out is to reboot.  The other printer modules in ImageFX
(postscript and Primera) work fine.

    @{i}[Mikey Note: I am looking into this ... ]@{ui}

  The only other minor problem is that since prt: acts like a file, I get a "PRT: file
exist, do you want to over write?" requester when  printing.  I just click "yes" and
it works.


     @{fg shine}@{bg fill} Dennis Griffin @{fg text}@{bg back}



  @{b}@{fg shine}TurboPrint Contributions@{ub}@{fg text}

I tried to use "netpar.device" together with TurboPrint (version 5.0). It works. I
configures TurboPrint to use the Workbench-printer-driver for postscript-printers and
send the output to "netpar.device". I can configure different printers and chose
between them (because TurboPrint lets you chose the device-number or port-number or
how this number is called). And I can still use the parallel.device for my local
printer. That's exactly what I want. I only realised one problem: I can chose between
different printer-settings. But after I have chosen any network- printer TurboPrint is
unable to use the normal printer connected to the parralel.device any more until the
next reboot. ("Device PAR: is unknown.") I do not know if this problem is caused by
NetParLpr or by TurboPrint or by the postscript-printer-driver. I do not use the
newest version of TurboPrint. I do not know if this problem occures in the newest
version, either.

     @{fg shine}@{bg fill} Martin Kluge @{fg text}@{bg back}

   @{i}[Mikey Note: I am looking into this one also......]@{ui}

#
@endnode

